abstract: After the election, Democrats debated whether to confront the president or seek compromise, but riled-up liberals have pushed party leaders into an all-out fight.
snippet: After the election, Democrats debated whether to confront the president or seek compromise, but riled-up liberals have pushed party leaders into an all-out fight.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Reduced to their weakest state in a generation, Democratic Party leaders will gather in two cities this weekend to plot strategy and select a new national chairman with the daunting task of rebuilding the party’s depleted organization. But senior Democratic officials concede that the blueprint has already been chosen for them — by an incensed army of liberals demanding no less than total war against President Trump.

abstract: A proxy race between party chairman candidates identified with Hillary Clinton and Bernie Sanders has drawn other contenders and a heated debate about the best way forward.
snippet: A proxy race between party chairman candidates identified with Hillary Clinton and Bernie Sanders has drawn other contenders and a heated debate about the best way forward.
lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — The outpouring of protests across the country has scrambled the contest for chairman of the Democratic National Committee two weeks before the vote, as party activists thrash out who should be the face of a newly energized party.

abstract: The party’s rightful outrage will mean nothing without the right strategy.
snippet: The party’s rightful outrage will mean nothing without the right strategy.
lead_paragraph: In one of many recent forums for the politicians vying to lead the Democratic National Committee — and, ideally, the party — out of the wilderness and into better times, the candidates were asked to distill the importance of fighting Donald Trump to 10 words or less.

headline_main: Are Democrats Falling Into Trump’s Trap?
headline_print_headline: Are Democrats Falling Into Trump’s Trap?

abstract: “If you try to go tweet-to-tweet with him, more often than not you’re not going to succeed,” a candidate to lead the Democratic National Committee said at a forum.
snippet: “If you try to go tweet-to-tweet with him, more often than not you’re not going to succeed,” a candidate to lead the Democratic National Committee said at a forum.
lead_paragraph: PHOENIX — As the candidates for chairman of the Democratic National Committee gathered here for a forum on Saturday, they wrestled with a vexing question: how to confront the asymmetrical political warfare of President-elect Donald J. Trump.

headline_main: When He Goes Low, They Go … Where? Democrats Mull How to Confront Trump
headline_print_headline: When He Goes Low, They Go … Where? The Left Mulls How to Resist Trump

abstract: Pete Buttigieg, the mayor of South Bend, says he wants to avoid a replay of the battle between Hillary Clinton and Bernie Sanders backers.
snippet: Pete Buttigieg, the mayor of South Bend, says he wants to avoid a replay of the battle between Hillary Clinton and Bernie Sanders backers.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Warning that beleaguered Democrats cannot afford a replay of their contentious presidential primary in the race to lead the Democratic National Committee, the mayor of South Bend, Ind., Pete Buttigieg, entered the  contest for party chairman on Thursday, presenting himself as an alternative to the two leading candidates.

abstract: A rising Democratic star in the Midwest makes you wonder about the barriers yet to be broken.
snippet: A rising Democratic star in the Midwest makes you wonder about the barriers yet to be broken.
lead_paragraph: South Bend, Ind. — IF you went into some laboratory to concoct a perfect Democratic candidate, you’d be hard pressed to improve on Pete Buttigieg, the 34-year-old second-term mayor of this Rust Belt city, where he grew up and now lives just two blocks from his parents.

abstract: As the gay marriage movement peaks, so does a debate about whether gay identity is dimming, overtaken by its own success.
snippet: As the gay marriage movement peaks, so does a debate about whether gay identity is dimming, overtaken by its own success.
lead_paragraph: From Capitol Hill in Seattle to Dupont Circle in Washington, gay bars and nightclubs have turned into vitamin stores, frozen yogurt shops and memories. Some of those that remain are filled increasingly with straight patrons, while many former customers say their social lives now revolve around preschools and playgrounds.

abstract: Although many thought the Indiana city was ruined when Studebaker closed its factory there in 1963, businesses say they have much to look forward to now.
snippet: Although many thought the Indiana city was ruined when Studebaker closed its factory there in 1963, businesses say they have much to look forward to now.
lead_paragraph: Foul weather in South Bend, Ind., on Friday didn’t stop a big crowd of Studebaker fans and area residents from coming to visit the former site of the automaker’s factory on the 50th anniversary of its closing. Jo McCoy, the director of marketing at the Studebaker National Museum, which opened a new exhibit Friday, said in a telephone interview that at least 800 people came through the museum.

abstract: The Mediterranean island-nation of Malta couples a tranquil, movie-set surface with an astoundingly rich past.
snippet: The Mediterranean island-nation of Malta couples a tranquil, movie-set surface with an astoundingly rich past.
lead_paragraph: Nicholas de Piro doesn’t look like a warrior monk. As the bespectacled grandfather padded around his 16th-century palazzo, pointing out curiosities like a gilded sedan chair and silver medical tools, he appeared more likely to offer me a cup of tea than slay anyone in the name of Christ. And yet that is the sort of thing Mr. de Piro’s order, the Knights of Malta (officially the Sovereign Hospitaller Order of the Knights of St. John of Jerusalem, of Rhodes and of Malta), were known for in their heyday. Drawn from the most noble families of Europe, they left their homelands, took vows of chastity and obedience and dedicated themselves to fighting infidels. The order no longer wages war, focusing instead on caring for the sick and poor. Until I arrived at Mr. de Piro’s doorstep on the Mediterranean island-nation of Malta, though, I’d had no idea that the Knights of Malta still existed.
